\details{
The SDT model assumes that for a given stimulus \code{truth} (0 or 1), sensory
evidence \code{x} is drawn from a normal distribution. When \code{truth} is 1, the
evidence is drawn from \code{N(dprime / 2, 1)}; when \code{truth} is 0, it's drawn
from \code{N(-dprime / 2, 1)}.
The \code{response} is 1 if \code{x > -c} and 0 otherwise. The decision criterion is thus \code{-c}.
The confidence rating is determined by which region the evidence \code{x} falls into,
defined by the confidence criteria \code{thetaone} and \code{thetazero}.
A rating of 0 corresponds to the lowest confidence (i.e., evidence closest to the decision criterion).

\strong{Parameter Interpretation:}
\itemize{
\item \code{dprime}: The sensitivity (d'). It reflects the observer's ability to distinguish between the two stimulus categories. Higher values indicate better performance.
\item \code{c}: The response bias. It reflects the observer's tendency to favor one response over the other, independent of the stimulus. A positive value indicates a bias towards response 1, and a negative value indicates a bias towards response 0. A value of 0 is unbiased.
\item \code{thetazero} & \code{thetaone}: The confidence criteria. These thresholds partition the evidence space into different confidence levels for each response.
\itemize{
\item For \code{response = 1}, \code{thetaone} are the criteria. They must be greater than the decision criterion (\code{-c}). For a given response, higher confidence ratings correspond to values of \code{x} further away from the decision criterion. For example, \code{confidence = 0} if \verb{-c < x < thetaone[1]}, \code{confidence = 1} if \verb{thetaone[1] < x < thetaone[2]}, and so on.
\item For \code{response = 0}, \code{thetazero} are the criteria. They must be less than the decision criterion (\code{-c}). For example, \code{confidence = 0} if \verb{thetazero[1] < x < -c}, \code{confidence = 1} if \verb{thetazero[2] < x < thetazero[1]}, and so on.
}
}
